   =20
      Goldman RTO
   =20
 =20

Goldman Sachs Group Inc. is back in the office:

Wall Street giant Goldman Sachs will lift all COVID protocols that have kep=
t some workers away as it pushes all employees to return to the office five=
 days a week after Labor Day, The Post has learned. ...
The official memo comes just days before the bank expects all employees to =
return to its offices five days a week, sources add.
=E2=80=9CThis is another way of Goldman Sachs saying, =E2=80=98School=E2=80=
=99s in session and we want you in person=E2=80=99 after Labor Day,=E2=80=
=9D Wells Fargo bank analyst Mike Mayo told The Post. =E2=80=9CGoldman is t=
he ultimate customer-facing firm and it=E2=80=99s tough to face customers r=
emotely.=E2=80=9D

Is that true? The customers don=E2=80=99t work at Goldman=E2=80=99s office.=
 Sometimes they visit Goldman=E2=80=99s offices, sure,=C2=A0but that=E2=80=
=99s usually a schlep for them and they mostly prefer not to. Generally if =
you are facing=C2=A0customers, it is (1) =E2=80=9Cremotely,=E2=80=9D by pho=
ne or email or Zoom or whatever, or (2) by flying to visit the customers at=
=C2=A0their=C2=A0offices. (Or, preferably, on the golf course.) Showing up =
at your office every day is not all that=C2=A0relevant=C2=A0to client-facin=
g-ness. And Goldman had record revenue in 2021, so whatever it was doing=C2=
=A0before=C2=A0school was in session seems to have worked fine.
Still there is obviously some sort of signal being sent here, perhaps to cl=
ients =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll be in the office if you call=E2=
=80=9D? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but certainly to employees and potential employees. =
It is some mix of:
=09We have a culture of collaboration, collegiality, mentorship, serendipit=
ous conversations at the water cooler, etc., and we all need to be together=
 with each other for that to work.=09We=E2=80=99re hardcore and in the offi=
ce all the time to prove it.

I can imagine that message being =E2=80=A6=C2=A0appealing? Not to everyone,=
 but you don=E2=80=99t need everyone. Back when I was an investment banker =
(disclosure: at Goldman), there was some sense that some banks were more in=
tense and worked longer hours than others. But it was all anecdotal; no ban=
k had, like, a formal seven-days-in-the-office-a-week policy. By the middle=
 of last decade there was a backlash to the intensity,=C2=A0and many banks =
(including Goldman) instituted formal=C2=A0not-seven-days-a-week policies, =
where junior bankers had =E2=80=9Cprotected weekends=E2=80=9D to prevent th=
em from working too hard. But it is possible that investment banking has be=
come too boring and too standardized, and that some banks will want to diff=
erentiate themselves as =E2=80=9Cwe are intense,=E2=80=9D and being early a=
nd uncompromising to a five-days-in-the-office requirement could be a crude=
 way to signal that. And then the intense young bankers will want to work a=
t Goldman and the more laid-back ones won=E2=80=99t. And then the intense o=
nes will get more of the plum private-equity jobs, because they are intense=
, and then everyone will want to work at Goldman to get those jobs. It has =
historically been hard for an investment bank to=C2=A0visibly=C2=A0signal t=
hat it is more intense than other investment banks. But return-to-office mi=
ght create some differences.
Or it might not and every bank will match this policy within a week, that i=
s also entirely possible.

