<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My basic view is that if you are a company tha=
t has become a meme stock, you should do an at-the-money offering to sell a=
s much stock as you can to retail investors at irrational prices. There are=
, however, reasonable objections to that view. Two are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You will want to be really careful ab=
out disclosure. If you sell a bunch of stock to retail investors at irratio=
nal prices, and then the stock drops, someone will sue you saying =E2=80=9C=
you didn=E2=80=99t tell me this price was irrational.=E2=80=9D There are de=
fenses there, but you need to be careful. Certainly if there=E2=80=99s any =
bad news that might come out, you=E2=80=99ll want to disclose it before the=
 stock offering, because you don=E2=80=99t want lawsuits of the form =E2=80=
=9CI bought your stock at irrational prices because I didn=E2=80=99t know a=
bout the bad news.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
You will have to get a bit lucky with timing. If you prepare a registration=
 statement and announce an at-the-money offering at the peak of meme-stock =
enthusiasm, shareholders might say =E2=80=9CYES MORE STOCK!=E2=80=9D and th=
e price might go up. But if you notice that you=E2=80=99re a meme stock and=
 then go off and=C2=A0prepare a registration statement and get lawyers comf=
ortable with it, that takes time, and by the time you are ready to launch t=
he offering you might not be a meme anymore.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bed Bath &amp; Beyond <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28907528.268558/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDgtMzEvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXNoYXJlcy1le=
