m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;"> strategy update deck</a>, and I suppose you can=E2=
=80=99t sell the stock without updating people on the strategy and financia=
l position.=C2=A0At noon today, the stock was at about $9.70.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don't know what to tell you. Here is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28907528.268558/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvODkxZThjMzUtNmFiZi00MDBlLTgzN2ItM2MwYzZiZmI2NTMy=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0f2f1b1e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a story about Bed Bath retail =
investors and Cohen</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On Wednesday, August 17, Cohen disclosed that =
he was selling his entire stake, and by Thursday he had fully closed his po=
sition with a gain of about $60mn. The sales sparked the worst one-day pull=
back in the history of Bed Bath &amp; Beyond stock.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While some retail investors took to Reddit to =
express dismay, still more rallied around Cohen. One wrote that it just =E2=
=80=9Cwasn=E2=80=99t like him=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cpull the rug out=E2=80=
=9D from under his followers. =E2=80=9CNot gonna lie=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=
=80=89.=E2=80=89did panic=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89but bought =
more. I have faith in him and this will make sense soon!=E2=80=9D said anot=
her user.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CCohen is the most highly regarded per=
son in these communities, after Keith Gill,=E2=80=9D said Christopher Karda=
tzke, co-founder of alternative data provider Quiver Quantitative, referrin=
g to a widely followed meme-stock trader better known by his YouTube userna=
me, Roaring Kitty. =E2=80=9CA lot of the interest in Bed Bath as a meme sto=
ck had to do with Ryan Cohen=E2=80=99s involvement.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CUsually a large insider sale is unani=
mously seen as a bad thing, but within this community there are theories th=
at maybe Cohen sold Bed Bath in order to create a merger with GameStop,=E2=
=80=9D Kardatzke said.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In order to =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what? Cohen=E2=80=
=99s meme-lord status comes mainly from the fact that he is the chairman of=
 the board at GameStop Corp., but he =E2=80=A6=C2=A0is not =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a=
 Bed Bath investor =E2=80=A6=C2=A0anymore? Why would he =E2=80=A6=C2=A0merg=
e them? I am so lost. But I guess that=E2=80=99s what it means to be a meme=
 stock. Nothing needs to make much sense.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other fact about Bed Bath &amp; Beyond tha=
t I like is this, from its most recent <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/28907528.268558/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0=
FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODg2MTU4LzAwMDA4ODYxNTgyMjAwMDA4MS9iYmJ5LTIwMjIwN=
TI4Lmh0bSNpODBiYWU5NmQ4YjAyNDM4Mjg1ZWRmNDlmM2MwODIzNGRfMzQ/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cB567a17e5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;"> Form 10-Q</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Between December 2004 and April 20=
21, the Company=E2=80=99s Board of Directors authorized, through several sh=
are repurchase programs, the repurchase of up to $12.950 billion of the Com=
pany=E2=80=99s shares of common stock. ... Since the initial authorization =
in December 2004, the aggregate total of common stock repurchased is approx=
imately 264.7 million shares for a total cost of approximately $11.728 bill=
ion.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In December 2004, Bed Bath=E2=80=99s market ca=
pitalization was about $12.5 billion, according to Bloomberg data. In the i=
ntervening 18 years, Bed Bath has spent a bit more than=C2=A0$11.7 billion =
buying back its stock; as of noon today, its market capitalization was a bi=
t less than $800 million. Those numbers add up almost exactly: Of the $12.5=
 billion that Bed Bath was worth in 2004, shareholders got paid back $11.7 =
billion (94%) in cash and $0.8 billion (6%) in remaining Bed Bath stock.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Bed Bath was doing stock buybacks=C2=A0<em>this year</em>, as its=
 business was deteriorating; in fact, the reason that Cohen re-disclosed hi=
s options position in August is that his ownership percentage had increased=
 due to those buybacks.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And now, after buying back 264.7 million share=
s at an average price of $44 per share for decades, Bed Bath needs cash and=
 wants to sell 12 million shares to whoever will buy them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general when some troubled brick-and-mortar=
 retailer has spent billions on stock buybacks, <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/28907528.268558/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMDgtMTQvdWJlci1hY3RpdmlzbS1hbmQtY29tbXVu=
aXN0LWJvYXJkcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODMxMjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA4MzEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd53db1e0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
I am not troubled</a>. Other people are: =E2=80=9CIf it had hung on to that=
 money, it wouldn=E2=80=99t be in trouble now,=E2=80=9D they say. I disagre=
e. The problem, often, is with long-term trends in the business. By sending=
 money out to shareholders when times were good, Bed Bath managed its decli=
ne gracefully. Sure today the company is worth a fraction of what it was wo=
rth a decade ago, but its shareholders, as a whole, did fine. They took som=
e of their value in shares in a declining company, but most of it in cash t=
hrown off by that company.But eventually you are left with some stub, a sma=
ller company with a lower stock price that has reached the end of its throw=
ing-off-cash phase. What do you do with that? Well, I dunno, the modern cor=
porate-finance approach is I guess that you make it a meme stock? By the ti=
me you have finished this graceful decline, your company (1) is in shaky fi=
nancial circumstances, so it attracts short sellers and (2) has some nostal=
gia value, because it was once a=C2=A0big name and now isn=E2=80=99t. That =
combination is valuable now! Now being a nostalgic company with shaky finan=
ces can attract a whole new shareholder base, a post-cash-flow shareholder =
base. You pay shareholders as much as you can with buybacks, and whatever=
=E2=80=99s left you sell to the meme people.</p>
